Substack Versus Writers
-----------------------

Twitter has, as I noted above, rolled back most of the restrictions on Subs=
tack links; I do suspect that tweets with Substack links will be even more =
penalized under Twitter=E2=80=99s algorithm than tweets-with-links already =
were, but we may never know. Still, all of this seems like a reasonable gam=
ble by Substack: the company is stuck at a $585 million valuation that seem=
s wildly out of whack for a company that had $12 million in revenue in 2021=
, and building a Twitter replacement seems like the sort of long-shot bet t=
hat is its only chance to earn that valuation.

We know that valuation because Substack asked its writers to fund a round (=
 https://www.axios.com/2023/04/07/substack-gets-writers-to-invest-but-doesn=
t-share-new-financial-info ) at the same $650 million valuation it achieved=
 in 2021, despite the fact the company failed to raise money last year ( ht=
tps://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/26/business/media/substack-venture-capital.ht=
ml ) ; the company eventually lowered its asking price to $585 million, but=
 never released its 2022 financials.

Frankly, I think this request was shameful: Substack has rightly earned the=
